Wow!<br><br>
Cook and SW, you make some very valid points.<br><br>
PTSD is not a descrete disorder, it is not even composed of descrete parts. It is an amorphous blend of may things that differs from person to person. There are some commonalities, but they cover broad areas. What is going on here, including the macho stories and the humor, is nothing more than what goes on with any group of combat vets seeking to learn from each other and help each other. Humor plays an important role in providing a needed breather at some points in time, as well as providing connections with each other.<br><br>
This stuff is FAR HEAVIER to many of us than what we are willing or able to communicate at this time. The subject must be approached cautiously, lest we trip out and loose it for days and weeks at a time. I have been known to check out for as long as three months! I  communicate heavier stuff during my closed trauma procesing group meetings than I do here. In time, more may be revealed, or not. It all depends. It all depends on how safe I feel.<br><br>
Doc, this is why you will *never* see a clinical and cold discussion of PTSD here. We are not clinicians. We are the victims. Emotion rules. Stick around and just watch. There is a chance that something will emerge that will challenge the most jaded clinician. I have been officially diagnosed with PTSD, and I just know.    
